column2:
['When using plain OpenGL (without Qt), a call to `glUniform` only has effect if the corresponding program is active (using `glUseProgram`). And since `QGLShaderProgram`&#39;s `setUniform` and `bind` functions ought to be simple wrappers around `glUniform` and `glUseProgram` respectively, you should change the order of function calls to:

    program-&gt;bind();
    program-&gt;setUniformValueArray(&quot;hitPoints&quot;, hitPoints, 40);

Thus always set uniforms of a program when the program is bound. But on the other hand the values of uniforms are persistent over binding and unbinding of programs, so you don&#39;t have to set them each time you bind the program if they don&#39;t change.

It&#39;s sad though that the documentation doesn&#39;t say anything about this issue. But since it names the GL functions that are wrapped by the corresponding Qt functions, I guess they just assume anyone messing with OpenGL to know about these facts anyway (in fact they are just lightweight wrappers and no new interface in itself).']

