column2:
['this is because you are using already defined function name e.g removeChild() or createElement()

avoid these known function which you think could have been used before. and try to change it to something uncommon like doSomthing();

']

column3:
['`removeChild()` is a [standard DOMnode moethod](https://developer.mozilla.org/En/DOM/Node.removeChild) which requires an argument and should be called from a node, and different browsers will respond with different errors if you attempt to use it the way you have.  Firefox returns the &quot;not enough arguments&quot; exception, while Chrome gives me &quot;Uncaught Error: NOT_FOUND_ERR: DOM Exception 8&quot;.

Rename your function to something else:

    // Rename...
    function removeChild(){
    // to...
    function someOtherRemoveChild(){

And call that in your markup instead.

    &lt;input type=&quot;button&quot; id=&quot;deleteChildButton&quot; value=&quot;Remove Child&quot; onClick=&quot;someOtherRemoveChild()&quot;/&gt;

Alternatively, since you defined `removeChild()` in `window` scope, you _should_ be able to call it via `window.removeChild()`, but I can&#39;t guarantee that will work, and it is weird to redefine DOM methods, so I don&#39;t actually recommend this:

    &lt;input type=&quot;button&quot; id=&quot;deleteChildButton&quot; value=&quot;Remove Child&quot; onClick=&quot;window.removeChild()&quot;/&gt;']

