column2:
['There is a redundant space between the `div` and the `#` sign which instead of selecting a div with specific `id`, selects an element with `id` within the div:

try changing: 
    
    $(&quot;div #&quot;+ id).toggle();

with:

    $(&quot;div#&quot;+ id).toggle(); // or $(&quot;#&quot;+ id).toggle()


']

column3:
['The [`var` keyword](https://developer.mozilla.org/en/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/var) declares function-scoped variables, opposed to block-scoped that you might&#39;ve expected. So, you only have 1 `id` that&#39;s shared by each iteration of the `for` loop. And, since the `click` function will be called after the loop has finished, `id` will always have the last value from the loop for this selector:

    ...function(){
        $(&quot;div#&quot;+ id).toggle();
    }...

You can fix this with an immediately-invoked function, which will [enclose](https://developer.mozilla.org/en/JavaScript/Guide/Closures) the variable for each iteration:

    for( i = 2 ; i &lt; trLen; i++ ) {
        (function () {
            var id = $(&quot;td.idout&quot;, &quot;tr:eq(&quot; + i + &quot;)&quot;).text();
            ...
        })();
    }

Or, [eventually](http://kangax.github.com/es5-compat-table/es6/), you&#39;ll be able to use the [`let` keyword](https://developer.mozilla.org/en/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/let) instead:

    for( i = 2 ; i &lt; trLen; i++ ) {
        let id = $(&quot;td.idout&quot;, &quot;tr:eq(&quot; + i + &quot;)&quot;).text();
        ...
    }']

