['There is a slight performance difference, due to the number of arguments being passed into the method.  For instance, look at the following classes:

    public class MyClassInstance
    {
        public int MyProperty { get; set; }
    
        public MyClassInstance(int prop)
        {
            MyProperty = prop;
        }
    
        public void IncrementInstance()
        {
            MyProperty++;
        }
    }
    
    public static class MyClassStatic
    {
        public static void IncrementStatic(this MyClassInstance i)
        {
            i.MyProperty++;
        }
    }

running the following code:

            DateTime d = DateTime.Now;

            MyClassInstance i = new MyClassInstance(0);

            for (int x = 0; x &lt; 10000000; x++)
            {
                i.IncrementInstance();
            }

            TimeSpan td = d - DateTime.Now;

            DateTime e = DateTime.Now;

            for (int x = 0; x &lt; 10000000; x++)
            {
                i.IncrementStatic();
            }

            TimeSpan te = e - DateTime.Now;

td = .2499 sec

te = .2655 sec

due to the fact that the instance method doesn&#39;t have to pass any arguments.

[heres][1] a slightly dated, but good article on performance


