['There are many ways you could do this: assuming the server architecture supports the [WSGI][1] standard, then you could do something as simple as plugging in your own handler to generate the HTML (this could just build a string manually if you want to be really straightforward, or else use a template engine like [Mako][2].

An example of a WSGI handler might look like this:

    class HelloWorldHandler(object):

        def __call__(self, environ, start_response):
            &quot;&quot;&quot;
            Processes a request for a webpage
            &quot;&quot;&quot;
            start_response(&#39;200 OK&#39;, [(&#39;Content-Type&#39;, &#39;text/html&#39;)])
            return &quot;&lt;p&gt;Hello world!&lt;/p&gt;&quot;

Obviously it is up to you what you return or how you generate it: as I say, for more complex pages a templating engine might be useful.
 
The more involved way would be to leverage a more complete framework, such as [paste][3] or [turbogears][4] but if you only want to output a static page or two this could be overkill.


  [1]: http://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0333/
  [2]: http://www.makotemplates.org/docs/
  [3]: http://pythonpaste.org/
  [4]: http://turbogears.org/']

column3:
['What you could do is provide a static WSDL which you can tweak and modify to your liking, before making it available.

In that case, the static WSDL is supplied &quot;as is&quot;, instead of querying the actual running service to create the WSDL &quot;on the fly&quot;. This can also be a performance boost.

In order to do this, you need to specify the name and location of the WSDL file like this:

    &lt;system.serviceModel&gt;
       &lt;behaviors&gt;
          &lt;serviceBehaviors&gt;
            &lt;behavior name=&quot;StaticWsdl&quot;&gt;
              &lt;serviceMetadata httpGetEnabled=&quot;true&quot; 
                   externalMetadataLocation=&quot;http://localhost:8000/YourService/YourWSDL.wsdl&quot;/&gt;
            &lt;/behavior&gt;
          &lt;/serviceBehaviors&gt;
       &lt;/behaviors&gt;


Now, whenever a request for the WSDL or Metadata comes in, this static WSDL will be provided instead.

This also allows you to create a single WSDL which contains all necessary information, including the XML schema for the data being passed around. No more importing or referencing external WSDL or XSD fragments.

Marc
']

